<TITLE> UK to review curfew system for terrorism suspects </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Sep 16, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain ordered a review on Wednesday of one of its main security measures, home curfews on terrorism suspects, after the country's highest court ruled the government had to disclose secret evidence held against them. Control orders, introduced just before 2005 London bombings that killed 52 people, allow terrorism suspects not charged with any crime to be kept under curfew for up to 16 hours a day, with tight restrictions on who they can communicate with or meet. Human rights and justice organisations say they violate fundamental rights and freedoms, with suspects placed under tight surveillance without knowing what they have done wrong. In June, Britain's top court ruled ministers had to reveal details collated by the intelligence services which could not be made public but which were used to justify placing suspects under control orders, a form of house arrest. Failure to disclose such evidence, which suspects were not privy to and could not challenge in court, breached their human rights, the law lords said. After that verdict, the government decided to revoke a control order against one suspect, known only as AF, rather than reveal the case against him. Home Secretary Alan Johnson said he believed the system was still worthwhile but had asked Lord Carlile, the independent reviewer of terrorism laws, to look at it again. "I have asked (Carlile) to review the impact of the House of Lords judgment and to advise me as to whether the assessment that the regime remains viable is right," he said in a statement to parliam
